<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-09-22T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-09-22T16:00:00-05:00" n="156" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d156">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">835.6363/462: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Weddell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos
                                        Aires</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-09-22T17:00:00-04:00">September 22, 1936—5
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 5:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>195. Department’s 124, September 21, 7 p.m. Standard Oil Company informs
                            me that Harden and Bronson,<note n="29" xml:id="d156fn29">In following
                                telegrams appears as Brousson, who was one of the directors of the
                                Dutch Shell-Mex Co.</note> now here discussing situation at length
                            with Argentine authorities, have sent them a joint letter containing
                            main objections to marketing arrangement. Standard Oil Company states
                            that idea of time limit to accept or reject arrangement has apparently
                            been abandoned for the present.</p>
                        <p>Will keep Department informed by telegraph.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Weddell</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>